1.Introduction

The purpose of this paper is to apply OLS linear regression to estimate the selling price of homes sold in San Francisco, driven by multiple related variables that may affect house prices and data.

The housing market is an important part of the US economy. A healthy housing market can promote economic development, employment and social prosperity (Alfiyatin et al., 2017). As the most valuable information in the real estate industry, the price of housing is the most desired news from the government and the company. Effective house price forecasts can help Zillow managers determine home prices and help their customers arrange the right time to buy a home (Chen et al., 2017). Therefore, it is very important to develop a model for predicting and identifying housing prices.

The project has encountered difficulties and has certain limitations. It is known to all that housing prices are a comprehensive and diverse outcome that is related to the interior characteristics of the house itself, the amenities, public characteristics, the city’s spatial structure, and even the development experience of San Francisco and the United States. Many of these many factors cannot be quantified by spatial data and added to the model, which leads to insufficient accuracy of the model. Also, the acquirement and pre-processing of data from different sources and in different format are challenging, and possible errors in the data are passed and accumulated to reduce the accuracy of the final model. In addition, the OLS linear regression model used in the study is hard to explain housing prices well, as many factors do not follow a linear state and it was too complex to use the OLS model on those factors.

The main strategy is to predict home prices by quantifying the relationship between house characteristics from the open data and known house prices. First, we calculate the distance from the spatial data surrounding to the corresponding house and perform buffer statistics for each house. The necessary predictors are then re-encoded to fit the OLS model to reduce errors and improve predictive performance through feature engineering. The p value, stepwise regression, and cross-validation results of the model were referenced to select significant variables to generate the optimal OLS model. After predicting 700 unknown home prices using the final model, Moran’s I was calculated to assess the extent of spatial autocorrelation not considered in this model, and the generalizabilities of race and income are evaluated eventually.

The final model of house price prediction is based on 31 predictors. The analysis of the sample shows that the median house price is very relevant to the number of stories and rooms, the built year, the distance to restaurants, the proportion of people under 18 years old, and the proportion of vacant houses. The final model we have developed explains roughly 73% of the variation in house prices in San Francisco (Adjusted R square as 0.73) within a 26.42% range of accuracy for price predicted (MAPE of 0.26). The Moran’s I of the model shows there is still a certain degree of spatial autocorrelation existing in error (Moran’s I as 0.041). The dichotomized race has nonregular distributed residuals, meaning that our model is conditional generalizable. For different groups our model works differently, in some situations MAE increases with MAPE decreases, while in other situations it turns out just the opposite. However, to a certain extent, we can believe that this OLS model is possible to work as a reference for Zillow predicting house price.

2.Data

To generate the prediction model, there are many variables from San Francisco Open Data used in addition to the house attributes in original dataset. The method for gathering the data can be divided into four techniques:

  • For already aggregated data of tracts, such as demographic data, the information are attributed to each house according to the census tract in which it falls.
  • For public service data related to relatively sparse resources, such as schools and police stations, the average distance from each house to the nearest n objects are calculated.
  • For relatively common occurrences data, such as street trees, the number of occurrences of the objects within an appropriate distance buffer area of each house are counted.
  • For predictors have meaningful attribute except geo-information, some of them are averaged in each house’s buffer area, and some category predicters are set as dummy variable by feature engineering.

We have 31 predictors used in final model and they fall in four categories:

  • Internal Characteristics: lot area, property area, built year, number of stories, number of rooms, number of beds, number of baths, sale year, sale month, property classes, zoning codes, construct types.
  • Amenities: city facilities, health centers, meter motoes, parking area, police stations, restaurants, schools, enterprise, street trees.
  • Public characteristic: eviction, traffic calming points, population density, percentage of people under 18, percentage of people over 65, percentage of vacant houses, percentage of people with bachelor’s degree or more, percentage of poverty, percentage of white residents, percentage of Asian residents, percentage of African American.
  • Spatial structure: name of neighborhood, police districts.

Scatterplots of Four Interesting Predictors and Sale Price

The following presents four interesting scatterplots between predictors and dependent variable: city facilities within 1/2 miles buffer, average distance to 5 nearest health centers, average distance to 3 nearest police station, and average distance to 5 nearest schools. City facilities varies in different types, such as parks and public squares, which are the cores of a city. The number of facilities that can be reached within 1/2miles buffer of the house, representing the convenience of the house to the public centers of the city. Health centers are the guarantees of people’s healthy life. People are increasingly aware that it is important to have a house near the health centers. In the scatterplot on the upper right, we can see that house prices are gradually decreasing as the average distance from the health centers increases. The police stations and schools have the same principle: people are eager to get close to the police station to protect their safety, and nearer schools provides convenience for kids attending schools. Thus, for the below scatterplots, both of their house price deceasing when the distances to police stations and schools increasing.

3.Methods

To predict the price of the houses, we use the OLS linear regression model, which contains 31 independent variables.

3.1 Data Wrangling

Data wrangling is the first step to clean all the data. All the data are set to same coordinate system and same format. One quarter of original data is separated as testing data and three quarters data serve as the training data. The NAs of numerical data are set as the average of other observations, and NAs of categorical data are set to unknown. The data wrangling helps us deal with the data with missing data and increase the prediction accuracy.

3.2 Feature Engineering

Different types of data are processed in different ways based on their characteristics for the model input. N nearest distance, buffer, and spatial join are used to generate the appropriate predictors in model. Some numerical variables are transformed into dummy variables to give more precise illustrations. The feature engineering helps use the raw data from open data source.

3.3 Model Feature Selection

There are four versions of models trained by us for selecting appropriate variables. We use k-fold cross-validation to test the consistency of the model. The k-fold cross-validation divides the training set into equal parts and uses them as test sets. We also use stepwise regression as a reference for choosing the right parameters, which allows our model to cover more valuable predictors. With the model feature collection, the data are more readable, and the model can fit better.

3.4 Spatial Structure Analysis

After obtaining the final model, Moran’s I was calculated to evaluate the spatial autocorrelation of the residuals, and the race and income dichotomization data were used to evaluate the model’s generalizability. The Zillow manager can visually observe the spatial autocorrelation results of model through Moran’s I and assess generalizability based on the table of different context data.

Test Set Result

d_2.test<-
  d_2.test %>%
  mutate(SalePrice.Predict = predict(regression, d_2.test),
         SalePrice.Error = SalePrice - SalePrice.Predict,
         SalePrice.AbsError = abs(SalePrice - SalePrice.Predict),
         SalePrice.APE = (abs(SalePrice - SalePrice.Predict)) / SalePrice)
#======== R square ==========
test.rsq <- cor(d_2.test$SalePrice, d_2.test$SalePrice.Predict, method = "pearson",use = "complete.obs") ^ 2
#======== MAE ==========
test.mae <- mean(d_2.test$SalePrice.AbsError, na.rm = T)

#======== MAPE ==========
test.mape <- mean(d_2.test$SalePrice.APE, na.rm = T)

#======== test.result table ==========
test.result <- matrix(c(test.rsq,test.mae,test.mape),ncol=3,byrow=TRUE)
colnames(test.result) <- c("R square","MAE","MAPE")
rownames(test.result) <- c("Test set")
test.result <- as.table(test.result)
test.result %>% kable() %>% kable_styling("striped", full_width = F)

Moran’s I test

d_2.test_predict <- d_2.test[which(d_2.test$SalePrice.Error != 0),]
coords.test <- d_2.test_predict %>%
  st_coordinates()

neighborList.test <- knn2nb(knearneigh(coords.test, 5))

spatialWeights.test <- nb2listw(neighborList.test, style="W")

d_2.test_predict$lagPriceError <- lag.listw(spatialWeights.test, d_2.test_predict$SalePrice.Error)

moranTest <- moran.mc(d_2.test_predict$SalePrice.Error, 
                      spatialWeights.test , nsim = 999)

To a certain extent, our model is generalizable. Because it can performs some similarity in different contexts. Looking at the MAE, it represents that our modelcan estimate low-income areas more accurately, and less effective in high-income areas. However, looking ata the MAPE, things have completely reversed. The model change to be more effective in high-income areas and majority-white area. The same thing happens in the racial context. MAE and MAPE showded some kind of complementarity, MAE is higher in majority-white area and MAPE is higher in majority non-white area. Although there are differences in each coefficient under different contexts, the average prediction accuracy of the model is similar to the overall average accuracy when we taking both MAE and MAPE into consideration, so the model has a certain generalizability.

5. Discussion

From the overall results, our model is effective in predicting the function of housing prices. Our R square is about 0.74, which means we can explain 73.50% house prices. In general, our model can be used as a reference for Zillow, but not as a decisive factor.

Our interest points to spatial data in the city, which reflects the potential link of geographic information to society. We have found that police stations, health centers, schools and other city facilities can greatly increase housing prices, reflecting the geographical orientation of people.

Our model can predict 73.50% house prices and the average difference between our house sales price prediction and real sales value is about 253871.2.The more important predictors of the model are the built year, the distance from near restaurants, and the percentage of the people under 18 years of age, which have large parameters.

According to our house sales price map, we can find there is spatial variation in prices. Through the Moran’s I result as 0.041 and the Moran’s I figure, there is spatial autocorrelation existing in our residual, which means spatial autocorrelation should be considered into our model.

Compared all MAE and MAPE in low-income area, high-income area, majority non-white people area, majority white people area, we can find all types of areas have one parameter increasing with the other parameter decreasing, so our model is conditional generalizable in different groups. It could be said that in majority non-white area our model performs better than in other three conditions a little. I think this might because non-white people are willing to live together, which make the prediction of this kind of area has significantly better MAE and a little worse MAPE.

6. Conclusion

Based on our study results, we would recommend our model to Zillow, but I will definitely add important hints - our findings can only be used as a secondary reference and not as a key determinant because of its poor accuracy. In addition, there is spatial autocorrelation that has not been solved in it. We have several aspects to be improved in the future Zillow’s use:

  • Apply spatial lag to quantify the spatial autocorrelation rather than leave it in residual.
  • Use more advanced feature engineering to transform variables, such as log or power functions, to make them perform better in the OLS model.
  • Improve the accuracy of existing data and discover more versions of the same period, rather than current data which varies over a decade.
  • Increase some undiscovered indicators into the model, especially those help predict high housing price areas
  • Try other types regression rather than OLS to reduce the error caused by nonlinear variables.

In this way, our model can provide Zillow with a better prediction of house sales price in the future.
